      <div class="full-width-section">
        <h1>How government works</h1>
        <p class="intro">The UK is a parliamentary democracy with the Queen as the Head 
        of State. The Prime Minister leads the government, and people vote 
        in elections for MPs who will represent them in Parliament.</p>
      </div>

      
      <h2>Who runs government</h2>
      <div class="halves-width-section prime-minister">
        <div class="one-half">
          <div class="inner-block">
            <%= image_tag 'how-gov-works/PM_01.jpg', alt: 'The Prime Minister' %>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="one-half">
          <div class="inner-block">
            <h3>The Prime Minister</h3>
            <p>The Prime Minister is appointed by the Queen after a 
            general election. He has a number of responsibilities 
            including:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>overseeing the Civil Service</li>
              <li>appointing members of the Cabinet, the committee 
              at the centre of the UK political system</li>
              <li>keeping the Queen informed about the work of 
              government</li>
            </ul>
            <p>The Prime Minister is based at Number 10 Downing 
            Street in London.</p>
            <p><a href="http://www.number10.gov.uk/" rel="external">For more information visit the Number 10 website</a></p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="thirds-width-section dep-prime-minister">
        <div class="two-thirds">
          <div class="inner-block">
            <h3>The Deputy Prime Minister</h3>
            <p>The Deputy Prime Minister is the deputy head of government and has 
              special responsibility for political and constitutional reform.</p>
            <p>He has additional responsibility for government policy areas, and is 
              consulted on all decisions involving the Prime Minister.</p>
            <p>The current Deputy Prime Minister is Nick Clegg MP.
            <p><a href="">Read more about his role and responsibilities</a></p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="one-third">
          <div class="inner-block">
            <%= image_tag 'how-gov-works/DPM_01.jpg', alt: 'The Deputy Prime Minister' %>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="thirds-width-section cabinet">
        <div class="two-thirds">
          <div class="inner-block">
            <h3>The Cabinet</h3>
            <%= image_tag 'how-gov-works/Cabinet_01.jpg', alt: 'The Cabinet' %><p>The Cabinet is the supreme decision-making body in government. Every 
              Tuesday during Parliament, members of the Cabinet (Secretaries of State 
              from all departments and some other ministers) meet to discuss the big 
              issues of the day.</p>
            <p><a href="">Find out more about the Cabinet
              on the Cabinet Office website</a></p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="one-third coalition">
          <div class="inner-block">
            <h3>The Coalition</h3>
            <%= image_tag 'how-gov-works/Coalition_01.jpg', alt: 'The Coalition' %>
            <p>The Conservative/Liberal 
                Democrat coalition government 
                was formed on 10 May 2010. The 
                Coalition Agreement sets out a 
                joint programme for government 
                based on shared ambition and 
                shared goals.</p>
                <p>Its programme of policies over 
                five years is to "rebuild the 
                economy, unlock social mobility, 
                mend the political system and 
                give people the power to call 
                the shots over the decisions that 
                affect their lives".</p>
            <p><a href="">Find out more </a></p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
        
     <h2>How government is run</h2>
      <div class="thirds-width-section depts">
        <div class="one-third">
          <div class="inner-block">
            <h3>Government departments and agencies</h3>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="two-thirds">
          <div class="inner-block">
            <p>Responsible for putting government policy into practice, departments and 
              their agencies also:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>advise, and are headed by ministers</li>
              <li>are staffed by civil servants</li>
              <li>are funded by Parliament</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Agencies are part of a department and provide government services, but 
              don’t set policy – this is done by the department.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="thirds-width-section">
        <div class="one-third">
          <div class="inner-block">
            <p><span class="feature-value">24</span>
              Ministerial departments
              <span class="feature-value">17</span>
              Non-ministerial departments
              <span class="feature-value">395</span>
              Other agencies &amp; public bodies</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="one-third">
          <div class="inner-block">
              <h3>Government departments</h3>
              <p>Some departments, like the 
                Ministry of Defence, cover the UK 
                as a whole. Other departments 
                don’t – for example, the 
                Department for Work and Pensions 
                covers England, Wales and 
                Scotland, but not Northern Ireland.</p>
              <h3>Executive agencies</h3>
              <p>These are part of government 
                departments and deliver 
                government services. They don’t 
                set policy – this is done by the 
                department that oversees the 
                agency.</p>
              <p>For example, Jobcentre Plus is an 
                executive agency and part of the 
                Department for Work and Pensions.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="one-third">
          <div class="inner-block">
            <h3>Other agencies &amp; public bodies</h3>
            <p>These work independently of 
              ministers but are accountable to 
              them. There are 2 main types of 
              NDPB.</p>
            <p>Executive NDPBs:</p>
            <p>These do work for the government 
              in specific areas. They have 
              varying degrees of independence. 
              Examples include Arts Council 
              England and the Environment 
              Agency.</p>
            <p>Advisory NDPBs:</p>
            <p>These are set up by ministers 
              to advise on particular matters. 
              Examples include the Committee 
              on Standards in Public Life and
              the Low Pay Commission.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      
      <div class="full-width-section ministers">
          <h3>Ministers</h3>
          <div class="feature-ministers">
            <p><span class="circle"><span class="count">01</span> <span>Prime Minister</span></span> + <span class="circle"><span class="count">33</span> <span>Cabinet ministers</span></span> + <span class="circle"><span class="count">64</span> <span>Other ministers</span></span> = <span class="circle"><span class="count">98</span> <span>Total ministers</span></span></div>
          <p>Ministers are chosen by the Prime Minister from the 
            elected members of the House of Commons and 
            House of Lords. They are responsible for the actions, 
            successes and failures of their respective departments.</p>
          <p><%= link_to "See full list of ministers", ministerial_roles_path %></p>
      </div>

      

      <div class="full-width-section civil-service">
         <h3>Civil Service</h3>
      </div>
      <div class="thirds-width-section civil-service">
        <div class="one-third">
          <div class="inner-block">
            <p class="civil-pie">Where civil<br />servants work</p>
            <table>
              <tr><td>23.1%</td><td>DWP</td></tr>
              <tr><td>15.9%</td><td>HMRC</td></tr>
              <tr><td>15.9%</td><td>MOJ</td></tr>
              <tr><td>15.3%</td><td>MOD</td></tr>
              <tr><td>29.8%</td><td>Other departments</td></tr>
            </table>
            <p>Almost three-quarters of 
            permanent civil servants work 
            at one of the four largest 
            departments.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="two-thirds">
          <div class="inner-block">
            <p>The Civil Service does the practical and administrative work of 
            government. It is co-ordinated and managed by the Prime Minister, in his 
            role as Minister for the Civil Service.</p>
            <p>Around half of all civil servants provide services direct to the public, 
            including:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>paying benefits and pensions</li>
              <li>running employment services</li>
              <li>staffing prisons</li>
              <li>issuing driving licences</li>
            </ul>
            <p>There’s more information, and job vacancies, on the Civil Service website.</p>
            <p><a href="">Visit the civil service website</a></p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>  

      <div class="full-width-section policy">
         <h3>What is a policy?</h3>
      </div>
      <div class="thirds-width-section">
        <div class="two-thirds">
          <div class="inner-block">
            
            <p>A policy is a statement of what the government is trying to achieve. 
            Government policy is the sum of all the individual policies – as a whole 
            they help to define where the government stands on broad political 
            issues. Separately they help to explain what the government is doing 
            and why.</p>
            <p>Listed by topic, on GOV.UK you can see all our policies and find out 
            exactly what we are doing, who’s involved, who we’re working with 
            (partner organisations) and who we’ve asked (consultations).</p>
            <p><a href="">See all topics</a></p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="one-third">
          <div class="inner-block">
            <p><span class="feature-value">1084</span></p>
            <p>There are currently 1084 policies being 
            implemented by government.</p>
            <p><a href="">See all policies</a></p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>  
      
      
      
      <div class="thirds-width-section legislation">
        <div class="one-third">
          <div class="inner-block">
            <h3>Legislation</h3>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="two-thirds">
          <div class="inner-block">
            <p>Laws go through several stages before they are passed by Parliament. The 
            House of Lords and the House of Commons work together to make them. </p>
            <p>They can include:</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        

        <div class="one-third">
          <div class="inner-block">
            <h4>White and green papers</h4>
            <p>White papers outline proposals for 
            new laws, and green papers ask for 
            public comments before the white 
            paper is published.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="one-third">
          <div class="inner-block">
            <h4>Bills</h4>
            <p>These are proposals for new laws 
            or changes to existing ones. Once 
            agreed by Parliament they have to 
            be approved by the Queen before 
            becoming law. The most common 
            type of bills are Public bills.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="one-third">
          <div class="inner-block">
            <h4>Acts of Parliament</h4>
            <p>These are bills which have been 
            approved by the Commons, 
            the Lords, and the Queen. The 
            relevant government department is 
            responsible for putting the act into 
            practice.</p>
            <p><a href="">Visit www.legislations.gov.uk</a></p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>  

      <div class="thirds-width-section access-infomation">
        <div class="one-third">
          <div class="inner-block">
            <h3>Access to information</h3>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="one-third">
          <div class="inner-block">
            <h4>Data</h4>
            <p>Freeing up public data and putting 
              it in people’s hands can help them 
              have more of a say in the reform of 
              public services. On data.gov.uk you 
              can easily access, review and build 
              on information about our country 
              and communities.</p>
            <p><a href="">See more</a></p>
